1. Definitions & notation

2. Types of sets


ID is: 3141 Seed is: 3308

Complementary sets: basic facts

Consider a set AA and a sample space SS.

  1. For set AA there is a complementary set, which has the name A′A′. Choose the best option below about A′A′.

    Answer:

    The set A′A′ ...

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Complementary sets do not share any elements.

    STEP: Use the definition of complementary sets to choose the correct answer
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    The question describes a situation with three sets: the sample space SS, another set AA, and the complement of set AA. A complementary set contains all of the elements in the sample space which are not in the original set. For example, if

    S={1;3;6;7;10}S={1;3;6;7;10}

    and

    A={6;7}A={6;7}

    then the complement of AA is

    A′={1;3;10}A′={1;3;10}

    Two things are always true about complementary sets.

    1. The complementary set will never include any numbers contained in the original set.
    2. The complementary set will always include all of the elements of the sample space which are not in the original set.

    The correct choice from the list is that the set A′A′ includes all of the elements which are not in AA.

    Submit your answer as:

  2. Which of the choices in the list is correct for the set (A∪A′)(A∪A′)? (Remember that SS is the sample space.)

    Answer:

    A∪A′=A∪A′=

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    This question asks about the union of sets AA with A′A′. Any set and its complement are like two sides of a coin: they are separate, but together they make the entire coin.

    STEP: Think about the union of the two sets
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    Let's continue to use the example where S={1;3;6;7;10}S={1;3;6;7;10}.

    We know that A′A′ is the complement of AA, so this means A′A′ has all the elements not in AA.

    If A={6;7}A={6;7} then A′={1;3;10}A′={1;3;10}.

    We are asked about (A∪A′)(A∪A′). This is sometimes written as (A or A′)(A or A′).

    (A∪A′)(A∪A′) means the elements that are in AA or in A′A′.

    A∪A′={1;3;6;7;10}=SA∪A′={1;3;6;7;10}=S

    The correct answer is: SS (the sample space).

    Submit your answer as:

Complementary sets: identifying a complementary set

Consider this sample space:

S={3;5;6;7;9}S={3;5;6;7;9}

Here is a set in the sample space:

X={3;5;6;7}X={3;5;6;7}

Identify set X′X′. Choose your answer from the list below.

Answer: X′=X′=
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

The symbol X′X′ refers to the complement of set XX. The complement of XX must include every element in S which is not in XX.

STEP: List the values which are in SS but not in XX
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

In this question we need to identify the correct set for X′X′, which is the complement of set XX. A complementary set includes all of the elements which are not included in the original set. Another way to think about it is like this: a set together with its complement will always contain all of the elements in the sample space.

In this case, we have the sample space:

S={3;5;6;7;9}S={3;5;6;7;9}

and the set:

X={3;5;6;7}X={3;5;6;7}

To find X′X′, take the elements in XX out of SS. Whatever elements remain belong in X′X′:

X′={9}X′={9}

In this case, there is 11 element which remains.

The answer above is not in the list of options in the question. Therefore, the answer to the question must be 'none of the above.'

    and we need to figure out how many elements are in it. This means we need to find out how many numbers are in the set.

    We need to interpret the set given to find out what numbers belong in the set. First, notice that the elements of SS are whole (counting) numbers because "x∈N0x∈N0". This alone means that the values come from:

    N0={0;1;2;3;4…}N0={0;1;2;3;4…}

Complementary events are two outcomes of an event that are the only two possible outcomes. If the one outcome is the A and BA and B, what is the only other possible outcome?

STEP: Which region or regions of the Venn diagram hold the elements A and BA and B? What is left over?
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

The question asked for: (A and B)′(A and B)′. In other words the complementary set of A and BA and B. So the first step is to identify the A and BA and B region on the diagram. The yellow shaded area below represents the region A and BA and B:

Represented as a set:

A and B={M;h}A and B={M;h}

A complementary set includes all of the elements which are not included in the set A and BA and B. If we take out all the elements from the shaded area above, then we are left with the only other elements, in the complementary set of A and BA and B.

(A and B)′={D;G;H;J;Y;f;q;u;z}(A and B)′={D;G;H;J;Y;f;q;u;z}

If you look at the diagram again this is all the elements which are in the green shaded area.

Therefore the correct set for (A and B)′={D;G;H;J;Y;f;q;u;z}(A and B)′={D;G;H;J;Y;f;q;u;z}.

Key misconception: set membership with overlapping sets

The Venn diagram below shows Sets AA and BB in the sample space SS. There are four numbers labelled on the diagram. They represent the number of outcomes in each region. For example, there are 33 different outcomes which are in neither Set AA nor Set BB.

Answer:

How many outcomes are there in Set AA only?

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

First you need to identify the correct region on the diagram for Set AA only. Then you can read off the number of outcomes included in that region.

STEP: Identify the correct region on the diagram and then read off the number of outcomes
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

We need to determine the number of outcomes which are in Set AA only. There are two numbers inside of Set AA's circle: the 77 is in Set AA but outside of Set BB. And the 44 is in both Set AA and Set BB. Which of these numbers should we use? To know, we must be aware of the following different statements in probability:

  1. Set AA only means the outcomes which are in Set AA but not in any other set.
  2. Set AA means every outcome in Set AA, even if they happen to be in another set.

We want the first case listed above. On the Venn diagram, Set AA only looks like this:

We can see that Set AA only contains just one number. That number represents every outcome which is only in Set AA (not in any other set).

Here are some examples to help show the impact of the word only:

  • Number of outcomes in AA only =7=7
  • Number of outcomes in AA =7+4=11=7+4=11
  • Number of outcomes in BB only =2=2
  • Number of outcomes in BB =2+4=6=2+4=6

The number of outcomes in Set AA only is 77.

STEP: Locate the union on the Venn diagram, and then read off the answer
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

The union of two sets is the combination of all of the elements in the two sets. For example, the union of all Matric students at a school and the school's rugby team will include every Matric student and all of the rugby players, including the ones who are not in Matric.

The union between set AA and set BB, also written as A or BA or B, can be shaded as shown below. All of the numbers in the shaded area belong in A or BA or B.

Therefore, the correct choice for A or BA or B is the set {2;3;5;6;7;8;9;10;11;14}.
